But this was not essential‚ because Aper’s hearers clearly understand that the propriety of the term ‘antiquos ac veteres' was not called into question, unless applied to Cicero and his immediate contempora ries, and so similarly, it is to them only that “ ex horum oratorum fama’ in the succeeding chapter can be made to refer.

For this reason, the emendation of ‘recentes' for ‘ veteres' must be rejected, quite apart from the circumstance that it is objectionable on other grounds, for (1) ‘recentes' would require the additional change of ‘ac' into ‘aut’3 (2) the modern orators are not so designated in the Dialogus, being called either ⁴ horum (nostrorum) temporum diserti (c. 1 5 14 15 36 4) ‘novi rhetores' (c. 14 24) or ⁶ nostri ' (c. 20 21 23 10 26 7). 29 adgnoscere: In c. 3 9 and 7 19 it signified ‘to recognise by the sense of sight.' Here the word is used of sense-perception generally, or, more particularly, with reference to the sense of hearing. No other instance of this latter meaning seems to occur. —eoniungere et copulare: The same verbs are combined in Cic. de orat. Ι 51, 222 coniungi (so Dr. J. S. Reid, iungi— MSS. edd.) copularique. ‘Adgnoscere' stands in causac relation to ‘coniun- gere,' hence joined by ‘ac’3 the synonyms coni. and cop. by ‘et.’ So similarly c. 32 5 scientia nos ornat atque . . . eminet et excellit.
